 1\n| year17 = [[1963 Canadian federal election|1963]]\n| party17a = Liberal\n| seats17a = 8\n| party17b = Social Credit\n| seats17b = 3\n| year18 = [[1962 Canadian federal election|1962]]\n| party18a = Liberal\n| seats18a = 3\n| party18b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats18b = 2\n| party18c = Social Credit\n| seats18c = 6\n| year19 = [[1958 Canadian federal election|1958]]\n| party19a = Liberal\n| seats19a = 2\n| party19b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats19b = 9\n| year20 = [[1957 Canadian federal election|1957]]\n| party20a = Liberal\n| seats20a = 8\n| party20b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats20b = 2\n| party20c = Independent\n| seats20c = 1\n| year21 = [[1953 Canadian federal election|1953]]\n| party21a = Liberal\n| seats21a = 9\n| party21b = Progressive Conservatives\n| seats21b = 1\n| party21c = Independent\n| seats21c = 1\n}}\n\n'''Canadian federal elections''' have provided the following '''results''' in '''Eastern Quebec'''.\n\n==Regional Profile==\nUntil 1984, this region of [[Quebec]] was [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] territory. [[Social Credit Party of Canada|Social Credit]] also did well here, winning in [[Rimouski]] and in [[Bellechasse (electoral district)|Bellechasse]] in 1979. [[Brian Mulroney]], a native of this area, was able to sweep this region for the Conservatives in 1984 and 1988, using the strong nationalist sentiment in the area.   That nationalist support transferred to the [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]], which dominated this region for the better part of two decades; the Liberals only won Montmagny in 1997 and the [[Bonaventure\u2014\u00celes-de-la-Madeleine|Bonaventure]] region in 1993. When the BQ experienced a decline in 2000, the Liberals were able to win in the [[Gasp\u00e9sie\u2014\u00celes-de-la-Madeleine|Gasp\u00e9]], and took [[L\u00e9vis, Quebec|L\u00e9vis]] in a by-election. When the Liberals collapsed in Quebec, the Bloc regained all their lost seats in 2004. One of those seats, however was lost to the [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservatives]] in 2006, and the Tories got another in a 2009.  Hopes of further Bloc gains were dashed in [[2011 Canadian federal election|2011]], as they were cut down to only one seat, with the NDP seizing one seat each from the Bloc and the Tories (the latter on a judicial recount).\n\n=== Votes by party throughout time ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Evolution of party standings throughout time\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"2\" scope=\"col\"|Party\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|1993\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|1997\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2000\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2004\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2006\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2008\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2011\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2015\n! colspan=\"2\"  scope=\"col\"|2019\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n!scope=\"col\"|Votes\n!scope=\"col\"|%\n|-\n| {{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|background}}|\n| |{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|name}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|72,292\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|26.8%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|81,291\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|31.4%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|95,889\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|39.5%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|58,181\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|28.7%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|31,741\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|14.4%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|44,091\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|21.3%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|24,762\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|11.2%\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|'''69,280'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|'''29.8%'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|57,523\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|24.5%\n|-\n| {{Canadian party colou